<subSubSection pageId="65" pageNumber="460" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="65.[165,1376,293,1467]" pageId="65" pageNumber="460">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[167,527,1041,1074]" pageId="65" pageNumber="460">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Endangered on The IUCN Red List. Extent of occurrence of Kelaart’s Long-clawed Shrew is probably less than 5000 km? and area of occupancy is probably less than 500 km?®. Its distribution is severely fragmented, and there is a continuing decline in extent and quality of its montane habitat. Kelaart’s Long-clawed Shrews have been found in Eravikulam National Park in Kerala (India) and Horton Plains National Park (Sri Lanka). They are largely threatened by agricultural and urban development that can potentially disturb or destroy restricted habitat. Virtually nothing is known ofthis unique lineage, and additional studies are needed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
